					2016 is the Year of VR
				</h2>
				

						
							
							
							
						
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1849166">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Immersive virtual reality headsets have been something people have been trying to make for decades now, and in the span of the next month consumer versions will finally be available. It's always been kind of a pipe dream, but improvements in technology have finally created headsets with a high enough resolution, frame rate, and low enough input lag to make a decent experience. While the barrier to entry is kind of high, I thought it might be fun to have a thread laying down the options in case anyone does decide to become an early adopter and try it. There's no rush, however, as this stuff is probably the future in the same way smartphones were the future once.<br />
<br />
The two major players are Oculus Rift, owned by Facebook, and the HTC Vive, in cooperation with Valve. They have similar capabilities with slight changes in the execution. The Oculus Rift launches on March 29th, while the Vive launches April 5th. The Rift launches at $600, while the Vive launches at $800. This is somewhat offset by the fact that the Vive is launching with it's special motion controllers, while the Rift comes with an Xbox One controller and the motion controllers not becoming available until later in the year. These special controllers are what enable hand tracking within a game while still giving a high level of control over the experience.<br />
<br />
System requirements are similar for both. You need an Nvidia GTX 970/Radeon R9 290 gpu, an Intel i5-4590 or better cpu, and 4-8 gigs of RAM. The Rift seems to require more USB ports, while the Vive requires a large room, as it uses lasers for motion tracking. I'm unsure if the Rift has anything like this, but the Vive also apparently syncs with your smart phone, and has a front facing camera, both designed to reduce the amount of isolation you get from putting on a VR headset.<br />
<br />
I'm unsure of the full extent of games and app support for the various platforms but the Rift launches with Lucky's Tale and Eve Valkyrie, while the Vive launches with Fantastic Contraption and Job Simulator.<br />
<br />
<br />
The third player is Sony with their Playstation VR, which won't launch until later this year. The technologies seem similar, and will run off of a PS4 instead of a PC, but details like price haven't been worked out yet.<br />
<br />
If you want VR on the cheap, you have a couple other options (which have actually been available for awhile). Google Cardboard and Samsung Gear VR. Both utilize your phone (Gear VR requiring a Samsung Galaxy), and both can be had for less than $100. As the equipment is less sophisticated and not built specifically for VR, the experience is not ideal, but it's a cheap way to try VR without the high cost.<br />
<br />
<br />
Links:<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.theverge.com/a/best-vr-headset-oculus-rift-samsung-gear-htc-vive-virtual-reality" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">A more in-depth rundown from The Verge</a><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.polygon.com/2016/1/15/10772026/virtual-reality-guide-oculus-google-cardboard-gear-vr" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">A similar guide from Polygon</a><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/virtual-reality/oculus-rift-vs-htc-vive/#" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Digitaltrends compares the Rift and Vive</a><br />
<br />
Valve actually has a tool within Steam to test if your computer is ready for Vive, for an Oculus tester refer to <a href="https://www.oculus.com/en-us/rift/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">their website.</a><br />
<br />
Now, I haven't actually been following this stuff that closely myself, but last year most of the games seemed more like tech demos and I was dubious as to what kind of support these systems would have at launch. A little googling has surprised me with how much is going to be available. These links include commentary and Youtube clips. As I haven't watched them all myself, I may post a few if any look particularly interesting later. I also encourage everyone else to post anything that looks interesting to them (Ackar posted a neat card game/rts in <a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78509-The-Conduit-developer-is-making-a-CCG-for-Oculus-Rift" target="_blank">Other Games</a> last week, for example).<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.wareable.com/oculus-rift/the-best-oculus-rift-games" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Wareable: Rift Games</a><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.wareable.com/vr/best-steam-vr-games" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Wareable: Steam VR Games</a><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.wareable.com/sony/best-playstation-vr-games-2016" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Wareable: Playstation VR Games</a><br />
<br />
<a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/oculus/comments/3z6iyi/list_of_full_oculus_rift_games_available_in_q1q2/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Reddit has an extensive list of 56 Oculus Rift games</a><br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2016-reality-check-what-steamvr-actually-offers" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Eurogamer</a> and <a href="http://www.polygon.com/features/2016/2/2/10885790/valve-htc-vive-preview-games" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Polygon</a> rave about Valve VR games.<br />
<br />
<br />
And finally, the only thing more fun than trying VR is watching someone else try VR. Simultaneously, the one thing that pushes support for new technology forward faster than video games is porn. So I leave you with a hilarious and NSFW (for subject matter and language, the video itself is censored) video of people reacting to trying VR porn for the first time. Not to derail the thread with that stuff already, but man it's funny. Be warned that this may lead you down a rabbit hole that is more scary than funny, but still funny.<br />
<br />
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gVatvg_UyEA" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Youtube: Buzzfeed (NSFW) </a>
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
