		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: 2016 is the Year of VR
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1849245">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Grindel</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=f65c4bd7286cdcffe68d99cdcc259a03&amp;p=1849233#post1849233" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Serious question here - how did they solve the seasickness issue? Because the last time I used a Rift I felt like I had to puke for the next 20 minutes.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>When was the last time you tried it? Was it DK1 by any chance? The Kickstarter version? The risk is likely always going to be there, but they have been working on mitigating the issue.<br />
<br />
The first thing they did was replace the LCD screen with an OLED screen, as well as increase the refresh rate. The problem is similar to motion sickness, where your brain and body disagree on what is actually happening to you, and the lower input lag is supposed to help.<br />
<br />
Beyond that, it may be a developer issue, in which you might find different results on a game by game basis depending on how savvy the design is in anticipating possible problems. Games that trick you into thinking you are moving when you are not are probably going to cause the most problems.<br />
<br />
<br />
Out of curiosity, because I haven't tried any of this myself yet, but would you compare the problem to the way certain older first person shooters would cause nausea? It sounds like a similar problem to me, perhaps magnified a few times.<br />
<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Ackar</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=f65c4bd7286cdcffe68d99cdcc259a03&amp;p=1849226#post1849226" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Augmented reality seems like it would be a good bridge to full VR.<br />
<br />
It layers virtual reality components over boring reality.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>That stuff is pretty cool, and probably more practical. Amusingly enough, it might actually be the goalpost, rather than the bridge. Microsoft's Hololens recently became available for developers, and it currently costs $3000. <br />
<br />
I'm not that into the current iterations. I think it needs to be wearable. Even before phones starting doing this stuff, handheld gaming consoles going as far back as the PSP were doing things like this, with the 3DS pushing major support for it in addition to the images being 3D, but the experience has always felt a little awkward to me. It doesn't feel like the fake thing is really there, because you are so preoccupied with holding the device in exactly the right way for it to work. The experience is also limited by the camera quality of the device you are using.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
