		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: 2016 is the Year of VR
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1849907">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Can't fault anyone for waiting. Early adopters always pay more for less. It's a gimmick/toy for people with money to burn, that will eventually (hopefully) become something more.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Tinthalas Tigris</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=f65c4bd7286cdcffe68d99cdcc259a03&amp;p=1849848#post1849848" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I stand corrected. <br />
<br />
PSBlog announced today that it will start at US$399. <br />
<br />
It is still out of the $300 I was limiting myself to purchase one at release, but I might actually get it by next christmas, or perhaps even the following.<br />
<br />
I try not to jump head first into anything at product launch, but I was going to give this one a go if they hit it for the 300 price point just for shits and giggles. But $400, really, is not too bad. <br />
<br />
I truly, truly hope that this does far better than any of its VR competitors, as it really has the best price point against all the others.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>$400 is what I expected. It's hard to guess how each will fare, but if I had to I would say that the Playstation VR is the short term mainstream device, while the Oculus/Vive are the long term mainstream device. At first, when there isn't much support, the lower price and gaming focus will make it easier for people to jump in. I sort of expect the PVR to be the gateway drug of VR but for the Oculus/Vive to have more growth potential. As technology and people's home PCs improve, and app support for non-gaming applications increase, the openness of the PC platform will likely result in the Oculus/Vive gaining wider appeal.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
